? Without a better understanding of the concept of reproduction (and what it means to say that an organism has reproduced), our thinking about parent–offspring relations and the ethical issues surrounding them risk being unprincipled. Here, I address that problem by offering a principled account of reproduction—the Overlap, Development and Persistence account—which I believe best captures the meaning of ‘genetic parenthood’.","topics":["ethics"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1093/pq/pqx032"},{"doi":"10.1093/pq/pqx014","title":"Against Intrinsic Interferers: A Critique of Kittle","authors":["Sungho Choi"],"journal":"pq","published":"2017-06-19","volume":"67","issue":"269","pages":"880-880","abstract":"","topics":[],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1093/pq/pqx014"},{"doi":"10.1093/pq/pqx028","title":"Contrast and Constitution","authors":["Peter van Elswyk"],"journal":"pq","published":"2017-06-13","volume":"68","issue":"270","pages":"158-174","abstract":"","topics":[],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1093/pq/pqx028"},{"doi":"10.1093/pq/pqx027","title":"The World We Live In (Phaenomenologica 220)","authors":["Michael Inwood"],"journal":"pq","published":"2017-06-13","volume":"68","issue":"271","pages":"424-426","abstract":"","topics":[],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1093/pq/pqx027"},{"doi":"10.1093/pq/pqx020","title":"Epistemology Personalized","authors":["Matthew A. Benton"],"journal":"pq","published":"2017-06-02","volume":"67","issue":"269","pages":"813-834","abstract":"","topics":["epistemology"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1093/pq/pqx020"},{"doi":"10.1093/pq/pqx016","title":"Bet Accepted: A Reply to Freitag","authors":["Christopher Dorst"],"journal":"pq","published":"2017-05-24","volume":"68","issue":"270","pages":"175-183","abstract":"","topics":[],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1093/pq/pqx016"},{"doi":"10.1093/pq/pqx026","title":"The Moving Spotlight: An Essay on Time and Ontology","authors":["Elena Fell"],"journal":"pq","published":"